<header class="header">
  <h1>Best Soil Mix for Seed Starting Trays</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    The best seed starting mix is the one that holds moisture evenly without becoming heavy, soggy, or compacted.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most home gardeners, the best soil mix for seed starting trays is a light, well-draining mix that retains moisture without staying wet or dense.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Seed starting mix is one of the most important parts of the entire process. It affects germination, root development, watering consistency, and overall plant health.
  </p>
  <p>
    A good mix creates a stable environment where seeds can sprout and seedlings can grow without struggling against poor drainage or uneven moisture.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Answer: What Soil Mix Works Best?</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Best for most gardeners:</strong> a light, fine-textured seed starting mix.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for consistent watering:</strong> mixes that balance moisture retention and drainage.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for beginners:</strong> high-quality pre-made seed starting mix.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    The goal is not rich soil. It is a stable, predictable growing medium for early growth.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What a Good Seed Starting Mix Actually Needs to Do</h2>

  <p>
    A seed starting mix should hold enough moisture to keep seeds hydrated while still allowing air to reach the roots.
  </p>

  <p>
    It should also stay loose over time. Compacted or heavy soil makes it harder for roots to develop and for water to move evenly through the tray.
  </p>

  <p>
    The best mixes create a balance between water retention and airflow.
  </p>
</section>

