<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What to Look For in a Seed Starting Mix</h2>

  <h3>1. Fine Texture</h3>
  <p>
    Smaller particles help seeds make good contact with the mix and improve germination consistency.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Good Drainage</h3>
  <p>
    Excess water should move through the mix easily without leaving it waterlogged.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Moisture Retention</h3>
  <p>
    The mix should stay evenly moist without drying out too quickly.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Light Structure</h3>
  <p>
    A light mix supports root growth and prevents compaction.
  </p>

  <h3>5. Consistency</h3>
  <p>
    The mix should behave predictably across the entire tray.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Bagged Mix vs DIY Mix</h2>

  <h3>Bagged Seed Starting Mix</h3>
  <p>
    The easiest and most consistent option. Most gardeners get the best results using a quality pre-made mix.
  </p>

  <h3>DIY Mix</h3>
  <p>
    Offers more control but requires balancing ingredients carefully. Small mistakes can lead to inconsistent results.
  </p>

  <p>
    For most home setups, bagged mix is the more reliable starting point.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Garden Soil Doesn’t Work Well</h2>

  <p>
    Garden soil is usually too dense and inconsistent for seed starting trays. It can compact easily, drain poorly, and create uneven moisture conditions.
  </p>

  <p>
    Seed starting requires a controlled environment, and garden soil is not designed for that purpose.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Overlook</h2>

  <p>
    One of the biggest issues is overwatering. Even a good mix can fail if it is kept too wet.
  </p>

  <p>
    Another common mistake is not pre-moistening the mix before planting. Dry mix often resists even watering at the start.
  </p>

  <p class="inlineNote">
    See <a href="/guides/when-to-water-seedlings/">when to water seedlings</a>.
  </p>
</section>

