<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Choosing Seed Starting Mix</h2>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>Using garden soil instead of seed mix.</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Choosing heavy or dense mixes.</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Ignoring drainage and airflow.</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Overwatering even good mixes.</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The best mix supports consistency, not extremes.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="calloutBox">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Should Actually Use</h2>

  <p>
    For most seed-starting trays, use a high-quality bagged seed starting mix that is light, fine-textured, and well-draining. Avoid garden soil and overly heavy mixes.
  </p>

  <p>
    Focus on consistency and ease of use rather than trying to optimize every ingredient. A reliable mix makes watering easier and improves overall seedling health.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    The best seed starting mix is the one that stays evenly moist, drains well, and supports steady early growth.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Bottom Line</h2>

  <p>
    The best soil mix for seed starting trays is one that balances moisture retention with drainage while remaining light and consistent.
  </p>

  <p>
    For most gardeners, a quality seed starting mix provides the best results with the least effort. The right mix creates a stable foundation for germination and early growth, making the rest of the seed-starting process easier to manage.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Choose a mix that supports balance and consistency from the start.
  </p>
</section>